. The results do not exhibit particular differences when an excess
amount of anode material is utilized, which is a valid observation. A remarkable improvement, however, is evi-
dent when the battery is cycled at a high C rate. In fact, at a 5 C rate, for the two electrodes made of 50 mg of LFP,
the specific capacities obtained are approximately 105 and 115 mAh·g
when LFP/LTO mass ratios of 1 and 0.85
are utilized, respectively. Under these conditions, a better retention capacity at high C rates should therefore be
obtained; however, additional results should be obtained to confirm this observation. Overall, the specific capac-
ities obtained are slightly lower when the anode and cathode loadings are increased especially at high C rates. For

The cyclability of a complete LFP/LTO battery made of 70 mg of active material is evaluated over 1000 cycles
at a 2 C rate after several cycles of formation (Fig.
). An initial discharge capacity of approximately 130 mAh·g
is obtained with a high capacity retention of ~91.6% after 1000 cycles. To the best of our knowledge, the foregoing
is one of the best results reported in literature for an all-paper full cell. In contrast, the LFP/LTO battery reported
by Cornell
et al
delivered an initial discharge capacity of 140 mAh·g
at C/10. Apart from a low coulombic effi-
ciency, a poor capacity retention of 87% is observed after only 20 cycles. The decrease in the active mass loading
